<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-22T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-22T06:00:00-05:00" n="549" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d549">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">661.9331/39: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-22T14:00:00+03:00">May 22,
                                    1941—2 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received May 22—1:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1024. I have learned from a reliable source that in connection with the
                            prolongation of the Soviet-Chinese trade agreement the Soviet Government
                            has agreed to continue sending war materials to Chiang Kai Shek and that
                            the Chinese deliveries are to consist primarily of minerals.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>